\begin_layout Subsection
t-channel at NLO
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The t-channel contributions at NLO are straightforward.
 We start with a leading-order (LO) 
\begin_inset Formula $sW^{+}\to c$
\end_inset

 process.
 We then add the next-to-leading-order (NLO) 
\begin_inset Formula $gW^{+}\to c\bar{s}$
\end_inset

 diagram; this exchanges an 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 quark in the t-channel, and thus will have a 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(m_{s}^{2}/Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 divergence for large 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 This is resolved by the subtraction (SUB) term 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{g}\otimes{\cal P}_{g\to s}\otimes\sigma_{sW^{+}\to c}$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{g\to s}$
\end_inset

 represents a perturbative splitting of 
\begin_inset Formula $g\to s$
\end_inset

; the SUB term is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{g\to s}\sim\frac{\alpha_{S}}{2\pi}\:P_{g\to s}^{(1)}\:\ln(m_{s}^{2}/Q^{2})$
\end_inset

, and will cancel the double counting between the LO and NLO graphs in the
 limit where the exchanged 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 quark becomes collinear.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here we use 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{g\to s}$
\end_inset

 to represent the perturbative splitting contribution which at NLO is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\alpha_{S}}{2\pi}\:P_{g\to s}^{(1)}\:\ln(m_{s}^{2}/Q^{2})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{g\to s}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 is the usual DGLAP splitting kernel.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The logarithmic divergence (mass singularity) will cancel between the NLO
 and SUB terms as 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}\to\infty$
\end_inset

, resulting in a finite result for the NLO t-channel contribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
u-channel at NLO
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The u-channel at NLO is more subtle.
 We definitely need the NLO 
\begin_inset Formula $gW^{+}\to c\bar{s}$
\end_inset

 diagram with a 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}$
\end_inset

 quark exchanged in the u-channel, and thus will have a 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(m_{c}^{2}/Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 divergence for large 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 This is resolved by the subtraction term 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{g}\otimes{\cal P}_{g\to\bar{c}}\otimes\sigma_{\bar{c}W^{+}\to\bar{s}}$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{g\to\bar{c}}$
\end_inset

 represents a perturbative splitting of 
\begin_inset Formula $g\to\bar{c}$
\end_inset

 and will cancel the double counting between the LO and NLO graphs in the
 limit where the exchanged 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}$
\end_inset

 quark becomes collinear.
 Here, the SUB term is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{g\to\bar{c}}\sim\frac{\alpha_{S}}{2\pi}\:P_{g\to\bar{c}}^{(1)}\:\ln(m_{c}^{2}/Q^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 The logarithmic divergence will cancel between the NLO and SUB terms as
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}\to\infty$
\end_inset

, resulting in a finite result for the NLO u-channel contribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Why do we need the LO (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}W^{+}\to\bar{s}$
\end_inset

)?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is not so obvious is that we need the LO 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

-channel process 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}W^{+}\to\bar{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that it is essential we include the subtraction SUB term 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{g}\otimes{\cal P}_{g\to\bar{c}}\otimes\sigma_{\bar{c}W^{+}\to\bar{s}}$
\end_inset

 so that we get a finite answer at large energies 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At energy scales 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\sim m_{c}$
\end_inset

, the LO and SUB terms remove the double counting between the LO and NLO
 processes.
 This is most apparent when you plot the individual terms versus the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 scale (or more properly, it is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 scale).
 [See Figure] In the region of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\sim m_{c}$
\end_inset

, the charm PDF 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{c}$
\end_inset

 (and hence, the LO contribution) rises very quickly as it is driven by
 the very large gluon, and coupled with a large 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{S}(m_{c})$
\end_inset

.
 The SUB subtraction also rises quickly as this is driven by the logarithmic
 term 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(m_{c}^{2}/Q^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 The difference LO-SUB is the physical contribution to the total (TOT=LO+NLO-SUB
), and it is this combination which is smooth across the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

turn on
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the charm PDF.
 We now see that if we neglect the LO (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}W^{+}\to\bar{s}$
\end_inset

) we loose the cancellation between LO and SUB in the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\sim m_{c}$
\end_inset

 and our structure function (or cross section) would have an anomalous shift
 at the location where we arbitrarily turn on the charm PDF.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So to recap, the combination of the LO and SUB terms ensure a minimal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

-variation at low 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 scales, and the combination of SUB and NLO ensure the mass singularities
 are canceled at high 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 scales.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
FFNS: u-channel for 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{F}=3$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us clarify the case where we work in a FFNS with 3 flavors 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u,d,s\}$
\end_inset

 but no charm PDF.
 In this case there is no LO (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}W^{+}\to\bar{s}$
\end_inset

) process as 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{c}=0$
\end_inset

, and there is no u-channel subtraction 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{g}\otimes{\cal P}_{g\to\bar{c}}\otimes\sigma_{\bar{c}W^{+}\to\bar{s}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is all perfectly consistent.
 However, the NLO u-channel process (
\begin_inset Formula $gW^{+}\to c\bar{s}$
\end_inset

) will have a potentially divergent 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(m_{c}^{2}/Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 contribution from the exchanged charm quark; this is fine so long as we
 don't go to large 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 If we do want large 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, then we will need to resum the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(m_{c}^{2}/Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 logs using the charm PDF.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We expect this FFNS to diverge from the VFNS result by contributions proportiona
l to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\frac{\alpha_{S}}{2\pi}\:\ln(m_{c}^{2}/Q^{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

